hands_on_practices.solution:
1. By rotational symmetry in Euclidean space, the integral must be proportional to the metric tensor $\delta_{\mu\nu}$:
$$I_{\mu\nu}
=\int\frac{d^4p}{(2\pi)^4}\frac{p_\mu p_\nu}{(p^2+\Delta)^4}
= A \delta_{\mu\nu}$$
To find the coefficient $A$, we can contract both sides with $\delta_{\mu\nu}$. Using $\delta_{\mu\nu}\delta_{\mu\nu} = 4$ and $\delta_{\mu\nu}p_\mu p_\nu = p^2$, we get:
$$I_{\mu\mu} = 4A = \int\frac{d^4p}{(2\pi)^4}\frac{p^2}{(p^2+\Delta)^4}$$
So, $I_{\mu\nu} = \delta_{\mu\nu} \frac{1}{4} \int\frac{d^4p}{(2\pi)^4}\frac{p^2}{(p^2+\Delta)^4}$.

2. We use the general formula for spherically symmetric integrals in $d$-dimensional Euclidean space:
$$\int\frac{d^d p}{(2\pi)^d}\frac{(p^2)^a}{(p^2+\Delta)^b}
=\frac{1}{(4\pi)^{d/2}\Gamma(b)}\Gamma\bigl(a+\tfrac d2\bigr)\Gamma\bigl(b-a-\tfrac d2\bigr)\,\Delta^{\,\tfrac d2+a-b} $$

3. For our scalar integral, we substitute $d=4$, $a=1$, and $b=4$:
$$
\int\frac{d^4p}{(2\pi)^4}\frac{p^2}{(p^2+\Delta)^4}
=\frac{1}{(4\pi)^{4/2}\Gamma(4)}\Gamma\bigl(1+\tfrac 42\bigr)\Gamma\bigl(4-1-\tfrac 42\bigr)\,\Delta^{4/2+1-4}
=\frac{1}{16\pi^2\Gamma(4)}\Gamma(3)\Gamma(1)\,\Delta^{-1}
$$
Using $\Gamma(4)=3!=6$ and $\Gamma(3)=2!=2$, and $\Gamma(1)=1$:
$$
\frac{1}{16\pi^2 \cdot 6}\cdot 2 \cdot 1 \cdot \Delta^{-1}
=\frac{2}{96\pi^2\,\Delta}
=\frac{1}{48\pi^2\,\Delta}
$$
4. Substituting this result back into our expression for $I_{\mu\nu}$:
$$I_{\mu\nu}
=\delta_{\mu\nu}\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{1}{48\pi^2\,\Delta}\right)
=\frac{\delta_{\mu\nu}}{192\pi^2\,\Delta}
$$
